        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer613376173" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer598582983205229065">Many detective stories start out with a bang. Something dramatic happens. &quot;Knots and Crosses,&quot; Rankin&apos;s first Rebus novel, and maybe his first novel altogether, is not that way. After 50+ pages, still not much had happened.<br/><br/>Most detective novels alternate scenes of tension and scenes of relief. Not this one. When the tension finally starts to build, it continues on an unrelenting screaming frightening path to the end of the story.<br/><br/>I guess you can tell I enjoyed the read. That&apos;s all I&apos;m going to sa</span>
  <span id="freeText598582983205229065" style="display:none">Many detective stories start out with a bang. Something dramatic happens. "Knots and Crosses," Rankin's first Rebus novel, and maybe his first novel altogether, is not that way. After 50+ pages, still not much had happened.<br /><br />Most detective novels alternate scenes of tension and scenes of relief. Not this one. When the tension finally starts to build, it continues on an unrelenting screaming frightening path to the end of the story.<br /><br />I guess you can tell I enjoyed the read. That's all I'm going to say since I don't want to reveal the plot. </span>
